statement:
Consider the diagonalizable matrix $A = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 \\ 
1 & 0.5
\end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 \\ 
2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 \\ 
0&0.5 
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 \\ 
2& 1
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}$

\textbf{(b)} Find the solution $x(t) =\begin{bmatrix}
x_1(t)\\ x_2(t)
\end{bmatrix}$ of the differential equation
$\displaystyle \frac{dx(t)}{dt} = Ax(t)$ satisfying the initial
condition $x_0 = \begin{bmatrix}
4\\1 
\end{bmatrix}$.

sols:
The solution for a differential equation of the form
$\frac{\mathrm{d}x }{\mathrm{d} t} = Ax(t)$ and A is 2 by 2 and
diagonalizable has the form

$x(t) = c_1v_1e^{\lambda_1 t} + c_2v_2e^{\lambda_2 t}$ where $\lambda$
are the eigenvalues of A and $v$ are their respective eigenvectors.

$c_1, c_2$ can be obtained by plugging in the initial condition
$x(0) = \begin{bmatrix}
4\\1

\end{bmatrix}$

Solving $\begin{bmatrix}
4\\ 1

\end{bmatrix} = c_1\begin{bmatrix}
1\\2

\end{bmatrix}
+ c_2\begin{bmatrix}
0\\1

\end{bmatrix}$ should give you $c_1 = 4, c_2 = -7$

therefore the solution is

$x(t) = 4e^{t}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\2

\end{bmatrix} - 7e^{0.5t}\begin{bmatrix}
0\\1

\end{bmatrix}$
